issue.title: Keyword teardown not executed if test timeout exceeded
issue.body:
Hi,

I have a user keyword that may leave a mess if it's not cleaned up after. So I have a user keyword teardown which does that. But if it is stopped early due to a test case timeout, the teardown is not executed. What to do?

Example:

```robot
# test.robot
*** Test Cases ***
Test with timeout
    [Timeout]    2s
    Keyword with teardown

Test which will find a mess
    Fail    Oh what a mess! Why did somebody not clean up after themselves!?


*** Keywords ***
Keyword with teardown
    [Setup]    Log    Doing the setup
    Sleep    24h    # This hangs
    [Teardown]    Log    Doing cleanup    # This is not executed, so how do I clean up?
```

Run:

```shell
$ robot test.robot
==============================================================================
Test                                                                          
==============================================================================
Test with timeout                                                     | FAIL |
Test timeout 2 seconds exceeded.

Also keyword teardown failed:
Test timeout 2 seconds exceeded.
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Test which will find a mess                                           | FAIL |
Oh what a mess! Why did somebody not clean up after themselves!?
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
Test                                                                  | FAIL |
2 tests, 0 passed, 2 failed
==============================================================================
Output:  /home/gschwaer/tests/robot-framework/output.xml
Log:     /home/gschwaer/tests/robot-framework/log.html
Report:  /home/gschwaer/tests/robot-framework/report.html
```

Unfortunately

- the documentation on [Test case timeout](https://robotframework.org/robotframework/latest/RobotFrameworkUserGuide.html#test-case-timeout) only talks about __Test case__ teardown,
- the documentation on [User keyword timeout](https://robotframework.org/robotframework/latest/RobotFrameworkUserGuide.html#user-keyword-timeout) is irrelevant here, and
- the documentation on [User keyword teardown](https://robotframework.org/robotframework/latest/RobotFrameworkUserGuide.html#user-keyword-setup-and-teardown) does not explain the behavior on any timeouts.

Thanks for you help in advance!

comment.body:
Hey @pekkaklarck,

I analyzed the bug (based on the ‚Äúreal test‚Äù by @gschwaer ): 
The problem seems to occur when:
**[Timeout] Test Test with timeout < [Execution Time] Keyword with teardown (here: Sleep)**
e.g. Test with timeout [Timeout] 20s  VS    Sleep 21s in Keyword with teardown

**Internally, the problem is as follows:**
After the keyword timeout (sleep vs timeout), `Cleanup` occurs in TearDown. 
This initializes **`Runner()` with a negative timeout**, which then leads directly to TearDown TimeoutError in `Runner.run()`.
Then the next test is continued with the `SuiteRunner`.
Observation: the negative timeout is **always around 0.007 seconds**. (even with varying times, as shown above)

**Reason/Fail Chain:**



`SuiteRunner()` sets the (current) context and the timeout contained therein (including `start_time`).

From this context, the (smallest) timeout is then extracted (still the same as at the beginning). A new
Runner is created from the timer for the keyword `Log    With this log mes...`. `Timout.time_left()` is used to calculate a time of about  0.007 seconds using `now() - start_time`.
The 0.007 seconds have elapsed since the last timeout due to the instruction execution.


How do you assess the problem @pekkaklarck ? Does it make sense to you? Are there any hints/suggestions/framework conditions for a fix by me? 
(This is my first contribution to open source ever. Please be lenient :) )

Best regards

issue.body:
**What this PR does / why we need it**:
The nightly build fails from time to time on unit tests, when trying to create dashboard handlers based on a non-exists directory of dashboard yamls.

The directory name is computed with:
```go
dir := path.Join(os.TempDir(), fmt.Sprint(time.Now().UTC().Unix()))
```

This pattern is used in two additional unit tests. The guess is that the directory is aleady exist, when the tests assumes it isn't.

This commit gives a unique directory name for each one of the tests that uses the temp directory name pattern, to ensure each test is using its own directory. Also, try to make these test more robust, by taking logic out of the `By` functions, and by adding some error checks.

**Release note**:
```release-note
None
```
